ce:section.ce:para:
Morphologies of CDs, AuNCs and CDs/AuNCs@ZIF-8 prepared in this work were characterized by transmission and scanning electron microscopies (TEM & SEM). Results reveal that both of CDs and AuNCs present a quasi-spherical shape. As shown in Fig. 1
                        A and 1B, diameters of CDs and AuNCs were 2.2 nm–5.0 nm and 1.2–2.2 nm, respectively, with the average values of 3.5 nm and 1.6 nm. Patterns of X-ray powder diffraction (XRD) indicate that introduction of CDs or AuNCs has insignificant influence on ZIF-8 structure (Fig. S1A). This is probably because of both the size and the concentration of CDs or AuNCs are much lower than those of ZIF-8 crystals [25,27]. Moreover, Fourier transform infrared absorption (FT-IR) spectra of the above materials were recorded (Fig. S1B). AuNCs displays characteristic absorption peaks at 1529 cm−1, 1642 cm−1, 2358 cm−1, 3114 cm−1, and 3415 cm−1 (Fig. S1B), corresponding to the stretching vibrations of Au–N, CO, S–H, C–H, O–H and N–H bonds [28], respectively. In comparison with ZIF-8, CDs/AuNCs@ZIF-8 shows extra absorption bands at 1311 cm−1 and 1572 cm−1, which are attributed to the symmetric and asymmetric stretching vibrations of COO− groups from CDs and AuNCs [29]. Furthermore, X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) measurements confirmed the existence of C, N, O, S, Zn, and Au elements in CDs/AuNCs@ZIF-8 (Fig. 2
                        ). As can be observed from the elemental mapping results of CDs/AuNCs@ZIF-8 (Fig. 3
                        ) obtained by energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX), all above elements are uniformly distributed, revealing the good integrity of constituents in CDs/AuNCs@ZIF-8. Other characterization results of the bove materials including ultraviolet–visible absorption (UV–Vis) and XPS were shown in the Supplementary Material file (Figs. S2 and S3). These results confirm that both AuNCs and CDs are encapsulated inside the ZIF-8 framework.
